<br>
At www.mormon.org, I found this faq. The question is &quot;are you christians&quot;<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE AUTOLINK START--><a href="http://www.mormon.org/question/faq/category/answer/0,9777,1601-1-55-2,00.html">www.mormon.org/question/f...-2,00.html</a><!--EZCODE AUTOLINK END--><br>
<br>
Here is the quote:<br>
<br>
We are Christians in a very real sense and that is coming to be more and more widely recognized. Once upon a time people everywhere said we are not Christians. They have come to recognize that we are, and that we have a very vital and dynamic religion based on the teachings of Jesus Christ. <br>
<br>
&quot;We, of course, accept Jesus Christ as our Leader, our King, our Savior. The dominant figure in the history of the world, the only perfect Man who ever walked the earth, the living Son of the living God. He is our Savior and our Redeemer through whose atoning sacrifice has come the opportunity of eternal life.&quot; <br>
<br>
Members of The Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints pray and worship in the name of Jesus Christ. He is the center of our faith and the head of our Church. The Book of Mormon is Another Testament of Jesus Christ and witnesses of His divinity, His life, and His Atonement. &quot;<br>
<br>
Sounds like christians to me. I'm not saying they arent cult like it their worship (though many Christian denominations have some cult-like qualities), but they do seem to be christians.<br>
<br>
BTW - On the topic of Mormons, you really need to go see Orgasmo if you have not. =)<br>
 <p><a href=http://www.adventurersanon.com/roster.php?selectedchar=29><img src=http://www.adventurersanon.com/images/sigs/alexz.gif border=0><a>
</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#F5F5DC><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub13.ezboard.com/ubremmin.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Bremmin</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/ezgfx/gicons/white_fire.gif" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br> <font color=#FF0000>(4/25/02 2:14:47 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub13.ezboard.com/fprexus95980general.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=16291.topic&index=31>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://kevin.purgatory.net/60x60rwb.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Evolution, PBS, a Religious man</span><hr size=1> Mormons profess to be Christians in part because it helps them to proselytize in the United States, where over 45 percent of the church's followers are located.<br>
<br>
Among reasons why many consider Mormons to be seperate from Christians is that they believe through practice of Mormonism anyone can become a god. In this way, Mormons are polytheists. Christianity is a monotheism based around the idea of the Holy Trinity, three aspects of the same deity.<br>
<br>
They believe that Christ was not divinely conceived by the Holy Spirit, but they instead believe that God came to Earth in his corporeal form and had sex with the Virgin Mary. <br>
<br>
In addition, they hold the belief that one mustn't necessarily adhere to the doctrines of Mormonism in order to be saved. If you died without having ever been exposed to their religion, you can be &quot;baptized after death&quot; at which point your spirit is given the opportunity to choose to be Mormon.<br>
<br>
While I have heard of some truly ridiculous beliefs held by organized religions, this one takes the cake. Taking into account that Joseph Smith, the man who wrote The Book of Mormon, wasn't born until the early 19th century, one is forced to hold to one of the following precepts as true:<br>
<br>
A) No one born between the birth of Christ and the emergence of Mormonism was judged at the time of their deaths, despite what it says in the New Testament of the Bible, which Mormonism also professes to believe in.<br>
<br>
B) Everyone who was born between the birth of Christ and the emergence of Mormonism was condemned to hell, whether or not they believed in the doctrines of Christianity. When these souls, who were condemned to hell, are baptized after death, they receive a get out of hell free card. They have a choice between going to heaven or remaining in hell for all of eternity. Despite the fact that they are in hell, proving that religion is true, some of them might say no. Riiiight.<br>
<br>
C) Until the emergence of Mormonism, Christianity was right. If you followed the previous doctrines, you went to heaven. But not anymore.<br>
<br>
The most likely belief is C. They also believe that newer prophets can &quot;override&quot; older prophets. This is a nice convenience, it makes it so they're never wrong.<br>
<br>
The list of differences goes on and on. From their former doctrine of polygamy, which was conveniently &quot;repealed by prophecy&quot; in order to save the State of Utah in 1890, to their belief that only men have the power of salvation (which, under Christianity, lies solely with Christ), and that once dead, they get to choose whether or not to exhalt their wives to godhood. <br>
<br>
For some very basic information, <!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.exmormon.org/fourteen.htm">here is another link</a><!--EZCODE LINK END-->, which can be found on the site I mentioned earlier.<br>
